Italy ' s Versace slashes prices to prepare for float . One of Italy ' s top fashion design houses , Gianni Versace , will continue to slash prices across its full range of designer clothes and accessories in preparation for a flotation on the Milan stock market by June 1998 . Santo Versace , brother of world renowned designer Gianni and chairman of the group Gianni Versace , said on Tuesday the group will continue to cut prices in its autumn / winter 1997 / 98 season giving average price cuts of 15 - 20 percent in the last two years . He hopes that the price cut move will boost volume sales and increase productivity and hence profit margins will be maintained . He stresses there will be no reduction in quality . Gianni Versace is due to show its autumn / winter 1997 / 98 collection at the Milan fashion show later this week . " We have cut our prices for the last three seasons and after the next season the average cut in prices will be 15 - 20 percent , " said Versace in an interview with Il Sole 24 Ore . He added that a planned flotation for the end of 1997 had to be delayed as the group wanted to complete its restructuring . He now sees a Milan listing by June 1998 , and adds that the group is interested in a listing on Wall Street . The Milan - based fashion house saw 1996 sales up 23 . 5 percent at 845 billion lire ( $ 500 million ) , which of 80 percent is sold abroad , and Versace sees a further 20 percent rise in sales in 1997 . Some 56 percent of sales were in clothing , with accessories accounting for 25 percent , perfumes 15 percent , and household furnishing items some four percent . Group pretax profits for the year 1996 rose 13 . 6 percent to 175 billion lire . ( $ 1 = 1 , 704 ) 
